{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657402/1923101301/0016.xml":{"full_text":"3.452,566 AUTOS\nGO TOSCRAP HEAP\nReplacing of Machines Made\nin 1916 and 1917 Great\nBoon to Manufacturers.\nBY J. C. ROVLE,\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, October 13.\u2014Who is\nbuying? the tremendous number of\nautomobiles being built this year, and\nwho will buy the more than four mil\nlion cars which will be built In 1924?\nThe answer to that question rests\nlargely on replacement needs. More\nthan two million present owners of\nautomobiles and trucks will be num\nbered among the purchasers In the\nnext twelve months. For the replace\nment requirements of the United States\nnow are more than two million cars a\nyear. This business alone, with the\ncollateral demand for parts, is sufficient\nto keep the automotive Industry mov\ning at a fair pace the year round.\nMillions of Autos Scrapped.\nManufacturers are not going to be\ncontent with a fair pace, however.\nProduction schedules the remainder of\nthis year and a large part of next give\npromise of being heavier than ever be\nfore. Price cuts by many manufac\nturers will necessitate the proportion\nate cutting of overhead per car, which\ncan only be assured by quantity produc\ntion. As a resist it is estimated that\nemployment in tpb Industry will be one\nthird \u2018greater tettt last year, through\nout the wintei r\nThe trementiijffj number of vehicles\nwhich will be thrown on the market\nIs not viewed with great alarm by\nmost manufacturers as they realize\nthat practically all the 1.583,617 cars\nmade In 1916 and the 1,868,949 cars\nturned out In 1917 are now on the\nscrap heap.\nLower Prices Seen Ahead.\nSince the cut In Ford prices, sentl-*\nment In the trade has settled down\nand no startling developments are ex\npected until the New York automobile\nshow, In January. Some makers are\nplanning fireworks for that occasion,\nwhich will evoke a long drawn \"ah\na-a-a\u201d from the public. One maker\npromises an Innovation in equipment,\nwhich, he says, will be, the biggest\nsensation in ten years. Another well\nknown maker is expected to announce\nnew low prices In connection with\nnew models which will shock the in\ndustry.\nIn the IRhantlme, sales throughout\nthe country are holding up unusually\nwell, acdofding to factory reports\nfrom dealers.\nKnortnoun Output Planned.\nPreliminary schedules of produc\ntion for the Ford Company for No\nvember and December Indicate an\noutturn of 1,900,000 for the current\nyear.\nThe remaining 112 leading makers\nare expected to turn out an equal num\nber which will bring the year\u2019s total to\nabout 3, SOU ,000 vehicles. The Ford\nCompany turned out its eight million\n(ive hundred thousandth motor October\n4. This shows a production of 500,000\ncars in seven days less than three\nmonths. Even if this rate were not ex\nceeded. the nine millionth motor should\nbe made about January 1 and the ten\nmillionth about July of next year. Sales\nof Ford cars and trucks In September\ntotaled 141,4 67. an increase of over\n35,000, as compared with September,\n1922.\nAutomobile Makers Buy Copper,\nAutomobile manufacturers are taking\nfull advantage of the present low price\nof copper to buy the red metal and cop\nper products In anticipation of their\nneeds. In other lines the demand has\nshown a falling off, due in some meas\nure to the usual seasonal decline. A\nshort time ago there was a movement\non foot to send copper to German fab\nricators without title to the metal pass\ning out of the hands of shippers. Under\nthis plan, the German manufacturers\nwere to turn it into manufactured goods\nwhich would be sent back to the ship\npers In this country who would market\nthem and remit to the fabricators the\ncost of manufacture with a profit added.\nThe recent disorganized condition of\nGerman industry, the almost complete\nloss of value of the mark as a medium\nof exchange and the growing belief\nthat German copper consumers have\nample funds in pounds and dollars to\nfinance copper purchases without such\naid has resulted In the dropping of this\nplan, at least temporarily.\nFURTHER DECLINE\nFORCED IN STOCKS\nCoppers, Steels, Bails and Oils Go\nLower in Week\u2019s\nTrading.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 13.\u2014Specula\ntive forces working for the decline\nmade further progress In this week\u2019s\nstock market, although the so-called\npivotal industrial stocks offered stub\nborn resistance to selling pressure i\naround their previous lows.\nThere were a few constructive news j\ndevelopments during the week such j\nas the declaration of the Sinclair divi\ndend, previously reported In danger; I\na new high record in railroad car i\nloadings; reports of larger Inquiries 1\nfor steel from railroad sources and j\nthe usual optimistic statements on the i\neconomic situation by banking and\nbusiness leaders, but the stock market j\npaid little or no attention to them, j\nCopper shares were sharply depress-I\ned. Anaconda and some of the minor j\nIssues falling to new low records for i\nthe year. Rubbers also lost ground, j\nThe continued shrinkage in the un- i\nfilled orders of the United States Steel\nCorporation and lessened production j\nhad a depressing effect on the steel\nshares. Motors and motor accessories\nwitnessed the usual seasonal liquids.- j\ntion.\nThe oils showed more stability, and j\nsugars developed Intervals of strength\non reports of higher commodity prices.\nRailroad shares were unable to\nmaintain the rally which set in late\nlast week, operations for the advance i\nbeing suspended when it was dls-\n(covered that they were attracting\nlittle outside participation.\nGermany\u2019s currency continued its j\ndownward course. French francs\nshowed marked Improvement.\nGASOUNE7 CENTS j\nA GALLON IN TEXAS\nPrice War in San Antonio Big\nHelp to Owners of Au\ntomobiles.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSAN ANTONIO. Tex., October 13.\nGasoline was retailing In many filling\nstations here today at 7 cents a gal\nlon. The price was believed to be\ntne lowest in the United States.\nThe Atlas Petroleum Company,\nwhich operates a refinery here, an\nnounced that because prices had been\nmanipulated without regard to cost\nIt would maintain the price at 7 cents\nuntil the market became stabilized,\nalthough no profit was made.\nThe Gulf company reduced its price\nfrom 13 to 11 certs Wednesday and\nwas followed by other major com\npanies Thursday.\nFINANCIAL\nI NEW YORK CURB MARKET\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The Star Office\nBY WILLIAM F. HEFFEHNAN.\nNEW YORK, October 13.\u2014Interest\nIn the curb market today was divided\nbetween Durant Motors and the oil\nshares. Durant had sold as low as 23\nI on Thursday, which was Its absolute\nlow record. It had closed at 25%.\nOn fairly active trading it jumped up\nduring the two hours today over five\npoints.\nDurant has long earned the right\nto be classed as a mystery stock. The\nway it was handled In the beginning\nhas been a matter of common crltl\n-5 dsm. Whether or not much stock\nwas sold to the public around the\nhigh prices Is not k-own. But the\nimpression is that a good many peo\nple were induced to buy on reports of\ntne extraordinary success which the\nDurant cars were having.\ns NEW YORK, October 13. \u2014Following\nis an official list of bonds and stocks\ntraded in on the New York Curb Mar\nket today;\nSales in BONDS,\nthousands High. Close,\nl 1 Allied Packers Bs.. 67% 67% 07%\n4 Alum 7s \u201925 102% 102% 102%\n1 Alum 7b new '33.. 106% 106% 108%\n5 Am Cot Oil 6s Oil 09 oo\nlAm Gas Elec 65.. 04% 04% 94%\n1 Am Light 6s 103% 103% 103%\nlAm Sumat Tob 7%a 06% 06% 06%\n6Am T At T 6s \u201924.. 100% 100% 100%\n3 Anaconda 6s 101% 101% 101%\n2 Anglo Am Oil 7%a 102 102 302\nBAr*Co of Del 5%s 80% 80% 80%\n6At(lftW ISS 5s 46% 46% 46%\n7 Beth Steel 7s '35.. 103 102% 102%\n10 Cent Steel 8s 107% 107% 107%\n1 Charcoal Co Am 8s 00 00 00\n0 1 P 98% 08% 08%\ni 2 Clt Serr <s C 88% 88% 88%\n15 Clt Serr 7s D 88% 88 88\n1 Co! Gr 8s part efs 18% 18% 18%\n3 ton Gas Balt 6s A 101% 101% 101%\n3 Cons Textiles 8s 04% 04% 04%\n1 ,1 r,lban Tp l 7%s 105 705* 105\n16 Kn Clt Ter 5%s w 1 00% 00% 09%\n1 Kenneoott Cop 75.. 303% 103% 103%\n8 Libby McN Lib 7s 09% 00% 00%\n6 Lig Win Llg r e 7s 102% 102% 102%\n1 Manitoba Pow 7s \\V 100 100 100\n4 Morris &Co 7%5.. 100% 100 300%\nI 1 New Or Pub Svrv 5s 84 84 84\n1 Ohio Power 5s B. 85 85 85\n2 Penn Pow Lt 'ss 86 86 SC\n30 Pub Serr of N J 7s 100% 100% 100%\n13 Pub Serr El Pow 6s 96 85% 05%\n1 8 O N Y 7s '2B 104 104 104\n1 8 O N Y 6%s 106 106 106\n3 Swift *Co 5s 91% 01% 01%\n5Un Oil 6s B \u201925 00% 00% 99%\n1 Vacuum OH 7s 106 106 106\nFOREIGN BONDS.\n4 Gvt of Argen 6s w i 09% 09% 99%\n2 King of Nether 6s. 98 98 08\n31 Swiss Govt 5%s 00% 99% 09%\n2 Swiss Govt 5s 97% 97% 97%\nSales STANDARD OIL ISSUES,\nin units.\n120 Buckeye P L 77% 76% 76%\n30 Cumberland P L.. 104 104 104\n30 111 P L 157 157 157\n80 Ind P L 00 89% 80%\n100 Inter'l Pet Co Ltd 15% 15% 15%\ni 100 Nat Transit 22% 22% 22%\n300 Ohio Oil new 55 54% 54%\n20 Prairie Oil Gas 167 167 367\n1 30 Prairie PL 09 98% 00\n3500 S O Ind 54% 54% 54%\n10 Southern PL.... 01% 01%\n10 S O Kansas new.. 30% 30% 39%\n100 SO Ky 01% 01% 01%\n100 8O N T new 41% 41% 41%\n500 Vacuum Oil new.. 50 49% 50\nSales INDEPENDENT OIL STOCKS,\nin hundreds.\n8 Ark Nat Gas 5% 5% 5%\n5 Carib Synd 3% 3% 3%\n1 Cities Service 130 129 130\n4 Cities Service pfd. 67% 67% 67%\n2 Clt Serv B cfa 13 12% 13\nSI,OOO Clt Serr C scrip. 70 70 70\n1 SI,OOO Clt Serv scrip 70 70 79\n8 Creole Synd 1% 1%\n1 Derh OSc Kef w i 5% 5% 5%\n30 Engineers Pet 05 .05 ,05\n10 Federal Oil 30 .30 .30\n1 Glen Rock Oil 70 .70 .70\n131 Gulf States Oil ..6% 6 6%\n15 Gulf States O&R 1% 1% 1%\n20 Hudson on 05 .05 .05\n110 Keystone Ranger.. .03 .03 .03\n79 Mex Oil 80 .74 .78\n2 Mex Panuco 80 .80 .80\nWORLDTRADENOW\nLOOKINGUPWARO\nBritain Notes Big Increase in\nExports\u2014Tourists Lavish\nWith Money Abroad.\nBy Cable to The Star and Chicago Dally News.\nCopyright, 1023.\nLONDON, October 13.\u2014World trade,\nso long depressed, has entered a new\nand better phase, with every Indica\ntion of rapid improvement, according\nto British bankers and economists.\nGreat Britain\u2019s trade figures for Sep\ntember, just published, show a re\nmarkable Increase In exports, amount\ning to \u00a33,700,000, over the figures for\nAugust.\nOrders for manufactured products,\nsuch as steel sheets and building ma\nterials. are flooding many Industrial\ncenters, especially in the Wales steel\nsection, where the output has been\nsold up to May of next year.\nHnpid Trade Expansion,\nThe rapid expansion of trade Is re\nsponsible for the recent astonishing\nstatements regarding plans for infla\ntion of the British currency. These\nplans naturally do not contemplate\nany positive Inflation of the pound\nsterling, but call for a negative pol\nicy designed to halt deflation, which\nmany authorities hold was carried\nI out far too rapidly.\nIn particular Instances, such as the\nWales steel industry, the upward\nmovement of trade has been In\nfluenced largely by the Japanese\nearthquake, which caused enormous\ndemands for construction materials,\nj Other elements, however, prove that\nthe world\u2019s buying power has been\nincreased generally, regardless of\nlocal Influences.\nSome Degree of Optimism,\ni For the first time since 1921, some\nj degree of optimism prevails In trad\nIng circles, replacing the gloomy fore\ni bodlngs occasioned by the French\nentry Into the Ruhr and Europe\u2019s fail\nj ure to settle the outstanding dilflcul\nj ties regarding reparations. Some\ndoubt exists as to whether the re-\nI covery of the world would, have been\naccelerated If France had not entered\nj the Ruhr, but that does not dimin-\nI ish the satisfaction over what recov\nery is now evident. It effectually\ni alienees the political prophets who\n1 held that occupation of the Ruhr\nj would definitely halt trade recovery,\nj Many British Industries face an ex\nceedingly hard winter, but apparently\nthe depression of these has been over\nj come by renewed vigor In other lines.\nTourists Flooding Europe.\nThe desire for travel, unsatisfied\nduring the long years of the war,\nshows no signs of diminishing after\nfive years of peace, and continues to\nI bring from the countries least af\nfected by the war thousands of pros\n-1 perous tourists. Americans In par\nticular have added vast sums to\nEurope\u2019s treasuries during the past\nseason, which began earlier and con\ntinued later into the autumn than\neven during the pre-war years. This\nstimulant of International trade In\nrecognized as one of the brightest\nomens.\nWOOL EXPOKTS HEAVY.\nBOSTON, October 13 I (Special).\u2014\nThe export movement of raw wool\ncontinues to feature activities In the\nlocal market. Otherwise, this week\nhas been one of the most disap\npointing to the trade for some time.\nWhat domestic demand there was\ncame largely for low grades and\nscoured wools. Quarter-blood fleeces\nsold at 47% cents in the grease and\nthree-eighths bloods at 52 cents.\nWEEKLY BANK BEPOET.\nNEW YORK. October 13.\u2014The ac\ntual condition of clearing house\nbanks and trust companies for the\nweek shows an excess in reserve of\n5J.4,624,210. Tills is a decrease In re\nserve of $1,330,000.\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON. D. C\u201e gATURDAY, OCTOBER 13. 1923.\nThe last few months attempts to\nsupport Durant stock in the markets\nt have been abandoned. It has been\nI left to take care of ftsslf, and the\nunloading even of small blocks has\n1 been attended by severe declines.\n1 A stock In this position la apt to\nhave an equally abrupt rally and it\nwas on\u00a9 of these rallies which\noccurred today.\nThe curb oils, like those on the\nstock exchange, had evidently got\nover what shock had been occasioned\nby the California price reductions\nt earlier In the week. Also reports\nthat production in the California ter\n-5 ritory was on the decrease had a\nf steadying effect. Vacuum oil, Stand\nard of Indiana and Prarle oil were\nall firm and fractionally higher. Inde\npendent oils, like Salt Creek, where\nthey were dealt in at all, were some\ns what higher.\nReading coal rights were In better\nf demand getting ready for their trans\ns fer to the stock exchange. duett\nSafety Razor rose a point.\nr 1 Mount Prod 14% 14% 14%\nI 1 Mutual Oil xot eft* 8% 8% 8%\n5 Now Brad OH w I 4% 4% 4%\n2 Peer Oil Corp 85 .83 .85\n10 Penn Bearer OIL, .55 .52 .55\n1 Pennoek Oii 11% 11% 11%\n2 Roy Pan Oil Ref 3% 3% 3%\n1 Salt Ok Pons 7% 7% 7%\n1 7 Salt Ck Prod 11* 18% 19\n1 32 Sapulpa Hefin 1% 1% 1%\n5 Seaboard Oil 1% 1% 1%\n10 Sou States Oil .15 .15 .15\n3 Turman Oil 65 65 65\n1 22 Wilcox Oil Gas. 4% 4% 4%\n10 Y Oil O\u2019* -01 *o<\nI INDUSTRIALS.\n3 Am Cot Fah pfd.. 101 90 101\n1 Atlantic Fruit w I 1% 1% 1%\n3 Bklyn Shoe 10% 10 10%\n1 Brlt-Am Tob Cou.. 24Vi 24% 24V1\n1 Bklyn Pity RR 11% 11% 11%\n26 Buddy Buds 1 ls\u00bb 1%\n1 1 Pentrlfug Iron Pipe 21 21 21\n1 5 Chi Nip new w i.. 38 38 3S\n1 Colo Pow Lt pfd 92 92 92\n2 Dnbiller C Radio 10 10 10\n37 Durant Motor 30% 26 30\n1 SrDurant Mot of Ind 8 7% 8\n1 Du Pont Motor* 433% 433 433%\n1 1 Gillette 8 R 260% 269 269%\n1 2 Gleaaonlte U>% 10% 10%\n3 Hudson Co pfd 16% 16% 16%\n1 2 Hartman new w i 39% 30% 30%\n2 Tnt Concrete 10% 10% 10%\n3 Kresge 35% 35% 35%\n2 Kreaee pfd 31 31 31\n2 Lehigh Power aec 22*4 22 22\n1 N Y Tel Co pfd... 109% 100% 100%\n2 Park Tilford.... 25% 25% 25%\n1 1 Radio Corp 2% 2% 2%\n1 Radio Corp pfd... 3rt 3A Si'c\n28 Read Coal rts w 1 22% 22 22%\n1 Heading Coal w 1 45% 48% 4H%\n1 10 So C I new .10 .10 .30\n1 Stud Wolff Rub Co 53% 53% 53%\n1 Swift Int 19 39 10\n3 Tob Prod Exporta. 4 3% 3%\n3 Un Pft Shir new.. 5% 5% 5%\n38 Un Retail Candy.. 5% 5% 5%\n1 2 U S Lt* Heat pf 1% 1% 1%\n3 Universal Pipe w i 17% 18% 17%\nMINING.\n60 Arizona Globe Cop .09 .09 .09\n13 Canarto Copper 1% 1% 1H\n30 Candelaria Min .05 .05 .05\n0 Con Cop Min new 2 2 2\n10 Cork Pror Mines..